04783nam a22009015i 9780520940772DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20072007cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209407727 a10.1525/97805209407722doi  a(DE-B1597)519914  a(OCoLC)176853923  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aGV863.A1 7aSPO0190002bisacsh04a796.3572221 aBurgos, Adrian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPlaying America's Game :bBaseball, Latinos, and the Color Line /cAdrian Burgos. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Crossroads ;v2300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Latinos Play America’s Game -- tPart 1. The Rise of America's Game and the Color Line -- tPart 2. Latinos and the Racial Divide -- tPart 3. Beyond Integration -- tConclusion: Still Playing America’s Game -- tAppendix: Pioneering Latinos -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough largely ignored by historians of both baseball in general and the Negro leagues in particular, Latinos have been a significant presence in organized baseball from the beginning. In this benchmark study on Latinos and professional baseball from the 1880s to the present, Adrian Burgos tells a compelling story of the men who negotiated the color line at every turn—passing as "Spanish" in the major leagues or seeking respect and acceptance in the Negro leagues. Burgos draws on archival materials from the U.S., Cuba, and Puerto Rico, as well as Spanish- and English-language publications and interviews with Negro league and major league players. He demonstrates how the manipulation of racial distinctions that allowed management to recruit and sign Latino players provided a template for Brooklyn Dodgers’ general manager Branch Rickey when he initiated the dismantling of the color line by signing Jackie Robinson in 1947. Burgos's extensive examination of Latino participation before and after Robinson's debut documents the ways in which inclusion did not signify equality and shows how notions of racialized difference have persisted for darker-skinned Latinos like Orestes ("Minnie") Miñoso, Roberto Clemente, and Sammy Sosa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBaseballzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aHispanic American baseball playersxHistory. 0aRacism in sportszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / History.2bisacsh  aamerican sports.  aathletes.  aathletic.  abaseball.  abranch rickey.  aequality.  ahispanic american demographic studies.  ahistory of baseball.  ahistory of sports.  aintegration of baseball.  aintegration.  ajackie robinson.  alatino baseball players.  alatinos.  aminnie minoso.  aorestes minoso.  aorganized baseball.  aprofessional sports.  arace in america.  aracial distinctions.  aracism in america.  aretrospective.  aroberto clemente.  asammy sosa.  asports.  athe color line.  aunited states of america.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025143440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094077240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520940772423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520940772/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY